This operation adds a flow variable to the local context. The variable is available in the current flow and its child flows.

Inputs\:
    keyName - The name of the flow variable to add.
    myValue - The value to assign to the flow variable.

Results\:
    returnResult - This is the primary output. It contains the value of "myValue" input field.

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.

Note\:
   If a flow variable with the same name already exists, its value will be overwritten.

d079fad4-5768-442b-a93c-87dea7ae955a.1a248eb8-f360-42ea-96ed-c415b0af1df6.description=
Attempts acquisition of a lock with an id given by the value of the lockId input.

Inputs\:
   lockId - the id of the lock, maximum 255 characters.

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully.

Result\:
   There are no results.

Notes\: 
    1. This operation associates an id (any string given by the user) with an execution or step/steps inside an flow execution. This operation is intended to be used in combination with "Realease Lock" or "Wait For Lock" to manage resources that are accessed at the same time (concurrently).
Example\: Using "Write to File" operation to write execution logs in a file, on the disk. The execution of "Write to File" should be made sequentially to assure the correct result. Using a sequence of "Acquire Lock" and "Wait for Lock" on "Write to File" step will assure a sequential execution and logs will be written on file without overlap. 
    2. The operation does not block waiting for a lock to become available.
    3. The locks acquired by this operation are not reentrant. This means that once a lock is acquired by a run, all subsequent attempts at acquiring the same lock by the same run (or any other run) will fail.
    4. Once a run terminates, all the locks that were acquired during the execution are automatically released. 
    5. The lock can be released manually using the "Release Lock" operation.
d079fad4-5768-442b-a93c-87dea7ae955a.1ba3d630-7f46-4bca-af01-0e0200af2814.description=
Deletes, from the Central database, the execution summaries that are older than the number of days specified by the lastXDays input. According to your selection, the execution summaries to be deleted include\: step log events, run inputs, run outputs and statuses. See the notes bellow for further details.

Inputs\:
    host - The host running the Central service.
Default value\: localhost
    port - The port the Central service is running on.
Default value\: 8080
    protocol - The protocol used to communicate to the Central service.
Default value\: http
Valid values\: http, https 
    authType - The type of authentication used by this operation when trying to execute the request on the target server. The authentication is not preemptive\: a plain request not including authentication info will be made and only when the server responds with a 'WWW-Authenticate' header the client will send required headers. If the server needs no authentication but you specify one in this input the request will work nevertheless. The client cannot choose the authentication method and there is no fallback so you have to know which one you need. If the web application and proxy use different authentication types, these must be specified like in the Example model. If the Central runs without authentication the "anonymous" value should be used. 
Default value\: basic
Valid values\: basic, anonymous.
    username - The username to use when connecting to the Central service.
    password - The password to use when connecting to the Central service.
    proxyHost - The proxy server used to access the web site.
    proxyPort -The proxy server port. Default\: 8080. Valid values\: -1 and numbers greater than 0.
    proxyUsername -The user name used when connecting to the proxy. The "authType" input will be used to choose authentication type. The "Basic" and "'Digest" proxy authentication types are supported.
    proxyPassword - The proxy server password associated with the proxyUsername input value.
    trustAllRoots - If true, enables weak security over SSL. A SSL certificate is trusted even if no trusted CA issued it.
Default value\: false 
Valid values\: true, false
    keystore - The pathname of the Java KeyStore file. You only need this if the server requires client authentication. If the protocol (specified by the URL) is not "https" or if trustAllRoots is "true" this input is ignored.
Default value\: /java/lib/security/cacerts
Format\: Java KeyStore (JKS)
    keystorePassword - The password associated with the KeyStore file. If trustAllRoots is false and keystore is empty, keystorePassword default will be supplied.
Default value\: changeit
    trustKeystore - The path of the truststore file. It may be empty if HTTPS server authentication is not to be used.
    trustPassword - Password to unlock the truststore. Provide this input only if trustKeystore is not empty.
    hostnameVerifier - Specifies the way the server hostname must match a domain name in the subject's Common Name (CN) or subjectAltName field of the X.509 certificate. Set this to "allow_all" to skip any checking. For the value "browser_compatible" the hostname verifier works the same way as Curl and Firefox. The hostname must match either the first CN, or any of the subject-alts. A wildcard can occur in the CN, and in any of the subject-alts. The only difference between "browser_compatible" and "strict" is that a wildcard (such as "*.foo.com") with "browser_compatible" matches all subdomains, including "a.b.foo.com"
Default value\: strict
Valid values\: strict, browser_compatible, allow_all
    deleteRunInputs - If true, deletes the run inputs.
Default value\: true
Valid values\: true, false
    deleteRunOutputs - If true, deletes the run outputs.
Default value\: true
Valid values\: true, false
    deleteStepLogs - If true, deletes the step logs.
Default value\: true
Valid values\: true, false 
    purgeStatuses - The statuses of the runs to be deleted, as a list with values separated by comma - accepted only on Central versions 10.50 or later.
Valid values\: COMPLETED, COMPLETED_ RESOLVED, COMPLETED_DIAGNOSED, COMPLETED_ERROR, COMPLETED_NO_ ACTION_TAKEN, SYSTEM_FAILURE, CANCELED.
Example\: COMPLETED_ERROR,SYSTEM_FAILURE,CANCELED
    lastXDays - The number of days threshold, specifying that the execution summaries that are older than 'lastXDays' ago are deleted.
Example\: 30
    maxAmount - Max number of executions whose inputs, outputs and steps will be purged. Setting this value to higher values than 1000 is only recommended for high-performance databases.
Default value\: 1000
    waitForLockTimeout - The maximum number of attempts to acquire the lock.
    delayBetweenRequests - Seconds to sleep between delete calls. Setting this value to higher values than 3 is only recommended for high-throughput systems.
Default value\: 5

Results\:
    returnResult - This is the primary output. Returns the amount of executions whose steps/inputs/outputs were purged. 
    exception - The java stacktrace of the runtime exception that occurred.

Responses\:
    success - The flow completed as stated in the description.
    failure - The flow completed unsuccessfully.

Notes\:
    1. If deleteRunInputs, deleteRunOutputs, deleteStepLogs inputs are all "false" and purgeStatuses is left empty then running the flow will purge all data for executions (including execution summaries).
    2. It is not recommended to trigger this flow twice in the same time, against the same target. It could cause damage to the database, depending on the database type.
d079fad4-5768-442b-a93c-87dea7ae955a.550ca85e-d913-425c-89fd-b1779bd188c1.description=
Compares two strings, returning a true response if and only if they contain the same sequence of characters. A null string is considered to be equal to an empty string.

Inputs\:
    string1 - The first string. 
Default value\: "" (empty)
    string2 - The second string.
Default value\: "" (empty)
    ignoreCase - If set to 'true', then the comparison ignores case considerations. The two strings are considered equal ignoring case if they are of the same length and corresponding characters in the two strings are equal ignoring case. If set to any value other than 'true', then the strings must match exactly to be considered equal.

Responses\:
    true - If the two strings are equal.
    false - If the two strings are not equal.

d079fad4-5768-442b-a93c-87dea7ae955a.c80f247c-2abc-46a7-afd5-2286d5255958.description=
Runs the requested SQL Command, returns the number of row(s) affected and any lateral effect.

Inputs\:
host	- Hostname or IP address of the SQL Server.
username	- The username of the SQL or Windows user credentials to login to the SQL Server.  If use Windows authentication, username input should be in the format like\: domain\username. 
password	- Password of the user account.
instance        - The named instance of SQL Server. Leave it blank for default instance.
dbPort	- The port on which the SQL Server database service is listening on.
database 	- The name of the database to run the command on.
authType	- Whether Windows authentication or SQL authentication should be used. Default is SQL.
command 	- The actual SQL command to run (either T-SQL, Stored Procedure, or Extended procedure).
timeout 	- Seconds to wait before timing out the SQL command execution. It defaults to 30 seconds.

Result\:
The number of rows affected.

Extra results\:
outputText -	 Output result for the command (if this is the case).

Responses\:
success 	- The command was successful.
failure 	- There was a problem running the command.

Notes\:
1. When informational commands (like dbcc) are run through the command, end the command with "with tableresults" in order to populate the outputText output with the obtained result.
2. Use the Sql Query operation instead of Sql Command when Select queries are to be run.
3. Please refer to the Notes in the Microsoft SQL folder description for the general integration information of Microsoft SQL Server.

d079fad4-5768-442b-a93c-87dea7ae955a.e35f91c4-f404-440a-a5f2-c2e0857f5b4f.description=
 Releases a lock with an id given by the value of the lockId input.

Inputs\:
   lockId - the id of the lock, maximum 255 characters.

Responses\:
   success - the only response returned.

Results\:
   There are no results.

Notes\:
    1. The operation only releases locks acquired by the current run. It cannot release another run's locks.
    2. The operation succeeds whether or not there is a lock held by the current run with the supplied id. 
    3. See the notes in "Acquire Lock" for a usage example.

d079fad4-5768-442b-a93c-87dea7ae955a.ee4f2887-a3ff-4833-be54-7606254b2530.description=
Deletes from the Central database, the debug events that are older than the number of days specified by the lastXDays input. Run this flow only on environments with authentication enabled and with ADMINISTRATOR permissions.

Inputs\:
    host - The host running the Central service.
Default value\: localhost
    port - The port the Central service is running on.
Default value\: 8080
    protocol - The protocol used to communicate to the Central service.
Default value\: http
Examples\: http, https
    username - The username to use when connecting to the Central service.
    password - The password to use when connecting to the Central service.
    trustAllRoots - If true, enables weak security over SSL. A SSL certificate is trusted even if no trusted CA issued it.
Default value\: false
    trustKeystore - The path of the truststore file. It may be empty if HTTPS server authentication is not to be used.
    trustPassword - Password to unlock the truststore. Provide this input only if trustKeystore is not empty.
    lastXDays - The number of days threshold, specifying that the debug events that are older than 'lastXDays' ago are deleted.
Example\: 30
    maxAmount - The size of the chunks in which to delete. The minimum value should be 100. Setting this value to higher values than 1000 is only recommended for high-performance databases.
Default value\: 10000
    delayBetweenRequests - Seconds to sleep between delete calls. Setting this value to higher values than 3 is only recommended for high-throughput systems.
Default value\: 5
    hostnameVerifier - Specifies the way the server hostname must match a domain name in the subject's Common Name (CN) or subjectAltName field of the X.509 certificate. Set this to "allow_all" to skip any checking. For the value "browser_compatible" the hostname verifier works the same way as Curl and Firefox. The hostname must match either the first CN, or any of the subject-alts. A wildcard can occur in the CN, and in any of the subject-alts. The only difference between "browser_compatible" and "strict" is that a wildcard (such as "*.foo.com") with "browser_compatible" matches all subdomains, including "a.b.foo.com"
Default value\: strict
Valid values\: strict,browser_compatible,allow_all
    waitForLockTimeout - The maximum number of attempts to acquire the lock.

Results\:
    returnResult - This is the primary output. A message containing information about the success or failure of the operation.
    exception - The java stacktrace of the runtime exception that occured.

Responses\:
    success - The flow completed as stated in the description.
    failure - The flow completed unsuccessfully.

Note\:
1) You may add these inputs\:
    proxy - The proxy server used to access the Central host.
    proxyPort - The proxy server port.
    proxyusername - The user name used when connecting to the proxy.
    proxyPassword - The proxy server password associated with the proxyUsername input value.
    keystore - The location of the KeyStore file - a URL or the local path to it. This input is empty if no HTTPS client authentication is used.
Example\: %JAVA_HOME%/jre/lib/security/cacerts
    keystorePassword - The password associated with the KeyStore file.
    authType - The type of authentication used to send the request to the Central service.
Default value\: anonymous - authentication not used when executing the request.
2) It is not recommended to trigger twice this flow, in the same time, against the same target. It could cause damage on the database, depending on the database type.
